# Report on the Effect of Daily Use of Twitter on the Attention Span of Under-16s

## Introduction

The pervasive use of social media platforms such as Twitter among adolescents has raised concerns about its impact on cognitive functions, particularly attention span. Under-16s represent a vulnerable demographic whose cognitive development is ongoing, making the examination of social media's effects on their attention span crucial. This report synthesizes findings from empirical studies, academic theses, and expert analyses to provide a comprehensive, evidence-based assessment of how daily Twitter use affects the attention span of individuals under 16 years old.

## Overview of Twitter Usage Among Adolescents

Twitter, a microblogging platform characterized by short messages (tweets) limited to 280 characters, is widely used by adolescents for self-expression, communication, information sharing, and social interaction. Its design encourages rapid consumption and production of information, often in fragmented forms ([Gleason, 2016](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/303795345_New_Literacies_Practices_of_Teenage_Twitter_Users)).

## Impact of Twitter on Attention Span: Empirical Evidence

### 1. Cognitive Performance and Learning Outcomes

A notable study by Barbetta et al. (2019) investigated the effects of Twitter use on high school students' academic performance in Italy. The study involved approximately 1,500 students who used Twitter as a tool to analyze a literary text versus a control group using traditional methods. Results indicated that Twitter use reduced test performance by 25 to 40 percent of a standard deviation, with the most significant decline observed among higher-achieving students ([Barbetta et al., 2019](https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/05/30/twitter-is-not-making-you-smarter-hurting-your-intelligence-new-study-finds/)).

This decline suggests that Twitter's format may encourage superficial engagement with content, leading to reduced comprehension and retention. The study posits two main reasons: a false sense of understanding from circulating tweets and time displacement from deeper reading.

### 2. Attention Deficit and Multitasking

Research highlights a correlation between frequent social media use and symptoms akin to Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD), such as shortened attention spans and distractibility. Wihbey (2013) notes that multitasking facilitated by social media platforms, including Twitter, can lead to cognitive deficits, particularly in adolescents who are still developing executive functions ([Wihbey, 2013](https://journalistsresource.org/studies/society/technology/multitasking-social-media-distraction-research-review/)).

The JAMA medical journal reports that ADHD is the most diagnosed disorder among U.S. teens, with 4.5 million children under 18 affected. The technological overload from constant social media engagement exacerbates difficulties in sustaining attention, especially in structured environments like classrooms ([Birim, 2016](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1877042816303305)).

### 3. Decreased Empathy and Emotional Regulation

Extended use of social networks has been linked to increased narcissistic traits and decreased empathy among teenagers. Larry Rosen's study at California State University found that 75% of teens with heavy social media use exhibited reduced empathy, which is crucial for social cognition and sustained attention ([Rosen, 2015](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/282715995_The_Impact_of_Social_Media_on_Adolescent_Development)).

Moreover, exposure to negative content on platforms like Twitter may increase vulnerability to mental health issues, including depression and suicidal ideation, which can impair concentration and cognitive functioning ([PLOS ONE, 2021](https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0246454)).

### 4. Addiction and Information Overload

The addictive nature of social media platforms contributes to shortened attention spans. A 2013 American research group study found that early childhood attention span predicts later academic success, implying that social media-induced attention deficits could have long-term educational consequences ([American Research Group, 2013](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3733218/)).

The UK Office for National Statistics (2015) reported that children addicted to social media often experience delays in emotional and social development, further affecting their ability to concentrate ([ONS, 2015](https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/wellbeing/articles/socialmediaandmentalhealth/2015)).

